      "writtenOn": "2020-10-21T14:42:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, there\u0027s no reason to ever use statement expressions in C++.  They\u0027re completely obsoleted by lambdas.\n\nThe lambda version is syntax sugar for\n\n    struct {\n        pthread_key_t operator() {\n            pthread_key_t key;\n            int result \u003d pthread_key_create(\u0026key, /*destructor\u003d*/nullptr);\n            if (result !\u003d 0) {\n                SK_ABORT(\"pthread_key_create failure: %d\", result);\n            }\n            return key;\n        }\n    } lambda;\n\n    static pthread_key_t sKey \u003d lambda();\n    return sKey;\n\nPlease use lambdas instead of writing out your own structs.  If you write your own struct in this situation, people will look at your code and think \"boy, that\u0027s weird, I wonder what\u0027s so tricky here that it can\u0027t be a lambda.\"  An immediately-invoked lambda is the preferred idiom of least surprise here.",
      "parentUuid": "509421c5_57002638",
      "revId": "9c7c40b4f71329f833d9bcb1eeb3d98c802caaf8",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
